Functions in SQL Server

  • Reusable routines that take parameters and return a value or table
  • Used to simplify logic and reduce repeated code
  • Can be used in SELECT, JOIN, WHERE, computed columns, etc.
  • Must always return a value
  • Read-only: cannot modify data
  • types: Built-in Functions and User-Defined Functions (UDFs)

Built-In Functions

SQL Server includes many built-in functions grouped by purpose. These are optimized and ready to use.

  • String Functions: LEN, SUBSTRING, REPLACE, CHARINDEX, LOWER/UPPER
  • Date & Time Functions: GETDATE, DATEADD, DATEDIFF, FORMAT
  • Mathematical Functions: ROUND, CEILING, FLOOR, ABS
  • Conversion Functions: CAST, CONVERT, PARSE
  • Aggregate Functions: SUM, COUNT, AVG, MIN, MAX
  • Logical Functions: IIF, CHOOSE
  • Metadata Functions: OBJECT_ID, COL_NAME, DB_NAME

User-Defined Functions (UDFs)

  • Custom functions created to reuse business logic
  • Used for business rules, reusable expressions, and formatting
  • Prefer Inline TVFs for better performance and execution plans
  • Advantages: Reusability , cleaner SQL
  • Limitations: Read-only, scalar UDFs may hurt performance when used per row
  • Scalar Functions: Return a single value (e.g., formatted code, calculated age)
  • Inline Table-Valued Functions (iTVF): Return a table from a single SELECT — fastest UDF type
  • Multi-Statement Table-Valued Functions (mTVF): Return a table built with multiplestatements

GROUP BY (Basics)

The GROUP BY clause groups rows that have the same values into summary rows.

  • Purpose: Aggregate data (SUM, COUNT, AVG, MAX, MIN).
  • Requirement: Any non-aggregated column in SELECT must appear in GROUP BY.
  • Usage: Summaries, totals, statistics.

Example:

SELECT PostTypeId, AVG(Score) AS AverageScore, MAX(Score) AS HighestScore, MIN(Score) AS LowestScore
FROM Posts
WHERE Title IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY PostTypeId;

GROUP BY Multiple Columns

You can group by more than one column to create more granular summaries.

  • Works like: Nested grouping — first by column A, then by column B.
  • Usage: When multiple dimensions are needed (e.g., Region + Department).
  • Behavior: Each unique combination becomes its own group.

Tip 💡: More columns = more specific groups.

Example:

SELECT OwnerUserId, PostTypeId, COUNT(*) AS PostCount, AVG(Score) AS AvgScore
FROM Posts
WHERE Title IS NOT NULL AND OwnerUserId IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY OwnerUserId, PostTypeId;

GROUP BY with HAVING

The HAVING clause filters groups after they are formed.

  • Difference from WHERE: WHERE filters rows; HAVING filters grouped results.
  • Usage: Used to filter aggregate values like COUNT, SUM, AVG

Tip 💡: Use HAVING when the condition depends on aggregated results.

Example:

SELECT OwnerUserId, COUNT(*) AS TotalPosts
FROM Posts
WHERE OwnerUserId IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY OwnerUserId
HAVING COUNT(*) > 10;

GROUP BY with JOIN

GROUP BY is often used with JOINs to summarize related data across tables.

  • Usage: Summaries across relationships (e.g., Orders per Customer).
  • Rule: Columns selected from joined tables must be aggregated or grouped.
  • Common pattern: JOIN → GROUP → aggregate.

Tip 💡: Perfect for reporting across related tables.

Example:

SELECT u.DisplayName, u.Reputation, COUNT(p.Id) AS TotalPosts, AVG(p.Score) AS AvgPostScore
FROM Users u
INNER JOIN Posts p ON u.Id = p.OwnerUserId
GROUP BY u.Id, u.DisplayName, u.Reputation;

What Is a Subquery?

  • A subquery is a query nested inside another SQL statement
  • Also called: Inner query, nested query.
  • Purpose: Used to pass results from one query to another
  • Placement: Can appear in SELECT, FROM, WHERE, HAVING.
  • Types: Single-value, multi-value, multi-column, correlated.

Tip 💡: Subqueries make your SQL dynamic by using data from other queries.

Types of Subqueries

  • Single-Row Subquery: Returns one value (used with =, <, >).

    • Example:

    SELECT DisplayName, Reputation, Location
FROM Users
WHERE Reputation > 
(
    SELECT AVG(Reputation) 
    FROM Users
);

  • Multi-Row Subquery: Returns multiple values (used with IN, ANY, ALL).

    • Example:

    SELECT Title, Score, OwnerUserId
FROM Posts
WHERE OwnerUserId IN 
(
    SELECT Id 
    FROM Users 
    WHERE Location IN ('New York', 'London', 'San Francisco')
);

  • Multi-Column Subquery: Returns multiple columns (used in tuple comparisons).
  • Correlated Subquery: Depends on each row from the outer query.

    • Example:

    SELECT DisplayName, Reputation, 
    (
        SELECT COUNT(*)  
        FROM Posts p  
        WHERE p.OwnerUserId = Users.Id
    ) AS TotalPosts,
    (
        SELECT COUNT(*)  
        FROM Badges b  
        WHERE b.UserId = Users.Id
    ) AS TotalBadges
FROM Users;

Subquery in WHERE

Used to filter rows based on values returned by another query.

  • Matches a single value: =, <, >
  • Matches a list/multiple values: IN
  • Used for comparisons: ANY, ALL

Example:

SELECT DisplayName, Reputation, Location
FROM Users
WHERE Reputation > 
(
    SELECT AVG(Reputation) 
    FROM Users
);

Subquery in SELECT

Subqueries in SELECT return a single value per row (scalar subqueries).

  • Returns one value: Single-row subquery only.
  • Used for: Calculated columns, lookups, dynamic computations.

Example:

SELECT Title, Score, 
    (
        SELECT AVG(Score) 
        FROM Posts
    ) AS AvgScore
FROM Posts
WHERE Title IS NOT NULL;

Subquery in FROM (Derived Table)

A subquery used as a temporary table (also called a derived table).

  • Must have an alias.
  • Used for: Pre-aggregation, filtering, complex transformations.
  • Behaves like: A virtual table created on-the-fly.

Example:

SELECT UserStats.OwnerUserId,  UserStats.TotalPosts,  UserStats.AvgScore,  u.DisplayName,  u.Reputation
FROM 
(
    SELECT  OwnerUserId, COUNT(*) AS TotalPosts, AVG(Score) AS AvgScore, 
    FROM Posts
    WHERE OwnerUserId IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY OwnerUserId
) AS UserStats
INNER JOIN Users u 
ON UserStats.OwnerUserId = u.Id
WHERE UserStats.TotalPosts > 5;

Set Operators in SQL Server (UNION Family)

Set operators combine result sets from two queries with compatible structures.

  • UNION — Combines and removes duplicates.
  • UNION ALL — Combines and keeps duplicates.
  • INTERSECT — Returns rows common to both queries.
  • EXCEPT — Returns rows from the first query not found in the second.

💡 Condition: Queries must return the same number of columns with compatible data types.

💡 Documentation Link: Set Operators

UNION

Merges two result sets and removes duplicate rows.

  • Ensures unique rows only.
  • Performs an implicit DISTINCT.
  • Slower than UNION ALL due to duplicate checking.

Example:

    SELECT Name FROM TableA
    UNION
    SELECT Name FROM TableB;

💡 Use When: You want a clean combined list without duplicates.

UNION

Example: 

SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
UNION
SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

UNION

Example: 

SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
UNION
SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

UNION ALL

Combines two result sets and keeps duplicates.

  • No DISTINCT is applied.
  • Faster than UNION.
  • Useful when duplicates are meaningful.

Example:

SELECT Name FROM TableA
UNION ALL
SELECT Name FROM TableB;

💡 Use When: Performance matters and duplicates are acceptable.

UNION ALL

Example: 

SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
UNION All
SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

INTERSECT

Returns only the rows that exist in both queries.

  • Behaves like mathematical intersection.
  • Removes duplicates automatically.
  • Useful for finding common items.

Example:

SELECT Name FROM TableA
INTERSECT
SELECT Name FROM TableB;

💡 Use When: You want the overlapping data between two sets.

INTERSECT

Example: 

SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
INTERSECT
SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

INTERSECT

Example: 

SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
INTERSECT
SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

EXCEPT

Returns rows from the first query that are NOT present in the second.

  • Removes duplicates automatically.
  • Order matters (A EXCEPT B ≠ B EXCEPT A).

Example:

SELECT Name FROM TableA
EXCEPT
SELECT Name FROM TableB;

💡 Use When: Finding “what’s new” or “what’s missing.”

EXCEPT

Example: 

SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
Except
SELECT St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

EXCEPT

Example: 

SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteCairoDatabase.dbo.Students
Except
SELECT St_Id , St_Fname
FROM RouteAlexDatabase.dbo.Students;

What is a Common Table Expression (CTE)?

A CTE is a temporary named result set in SQL Server that you can reference within a SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE statement.

  • Defined using the WITH keyword.
  • Improves readability and organization of complex queries.
  • Exists only for the duration of the query execution.

💡 Note: CTEs are similar to derived tables but can be referenced multiple times within the same query.

Documentation Link: WITH common_table_expression

CTE Syntax

Example:

WITH cte_name (column1, column2, ...) AS 
(
    SELECT statement
)
SELECT * FROM cte_name;

Key points:

  • The CTE must be followed by a single query that references it.
  • Column list is optional; if omitted, columns are inferred from the SELECT.

Recursive CTEs

CTEs can call themselves recursively, useful for hierarchical data like org charts or tree structures.

  • Has two parts: anchor member (base query) and recursive member.
  • Executes repeatedly until no more rows are returned.

Key points:

  • Must use UNION ALL
  • Anchor + Recursive members required

💡 Tip: Use OPTION (MAXRECURSION n) to limit recursion depth.

Documentation Link: Recursive CTEs

SELECT INTO

Purpose: Create a new table and insert data into it in a single step.

  • Creates a new table automatically.
  • Copies structure + data from the SELECT query.
  • No need to define columns beforehand.
  • Useful for backups, archiving, or temporary table creation.

💡 Note: SELECT INTO fails if the target table already exists.

Documentation Link: Select - Into Clause

SELECT INTO — Syntax & Example

Syntax

SELECT columns
INTO NewTable
FROM ExistingTable;

Example:

SELECT *
INTO EmployeesBackup
FROM Employees
WHERE Status = 'Active';

💡 Tip: SELECT INTO copies only column definitions — not indexes, constraints, or keys.

SELECT INTO with Joins & Filtering

SELECT INTO can be used with:

  • JOINs
  • Aggregations
  • WHERE filters
  • Computed columns

Example:

SELECT e.EmployeeName, d.DepartmentName
INTO EmployeeDepartmentReport
FROM Employees e 
JOIN Departments d
ON e.DepartmentId = d.Id
WHERE d.IsActive = 1;

💡 Use Case: Quickly generate reporting tables or export snapshots.

User-Defined Functions (UDFs)

User-defined functions allow you to encapsulate reusable logic and return values that can be used in queries.

  • Written by the developer to perform custom operations.
  • Must return a value (scalar or table).
  • Cannot modify database state (no INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
  • Deterministic behavior recommended for indexing and performance.
  • Enhances code reuse and query readability.

💡 UDFs behave like functions in programming languages — input parameters, processing, and a return value.

Types of UDFs

SQL Server supports three main types of user-defined functions:

  • Scalar UDF
    Returns a single value (INT, VARCHAR, DATE, etc.).
  • Inline Table-Valued Function (iTVF)
    Returns a table using a single SELECT statement.
  • Multi-Statement Table-Valued Function (mTVF)
    Returns a table built with multiple statements and logic.

💡 Inline TVFs are the fastest — they behave like views with parameters.

Scalar Functions

Scalar UDFs return a single value of any supported data type.

  • Accept parameters.
  • Contain logic using expressions and built-in functions.
  • Useful for formatting, calculations, transformations.

Example:

CREATE FUNCTION dbo.GetFullName ( @First NVARCHAR(50) , @Last NVARCHAR(50))
RETURNS NVARCHAR(120)
AS
BEGIN
    RETURN @First + ' ' + @Last;
END;

💡 Best for reusable business logic that returns a single computed value.

Inline Table-Valued Functions

Return a table using a single SELECT statement. They are optimized and perform very well.

  • No BEGIN/END block.
  • Behaves like a parameterized view.
  • Fastest type of UDF.

Example:

CREATE FUNCTION dbo.GetEmployeesByDept ( @DeptId INT )
RETURNS TABLE
AS
    RETURN ( SELECT * FROM Employees WHERE DepartmentId = @DeptId )

💡 Inline TVFs allow query optimizer to rewrite and merge execution plans efficiently.

Multi-Statement Table-Valued Functions

Return a table variable that can be filled using multiple statements.

  • Contain BEGIN/END.
  • Allow complex logic and conditional processing.
  • Slower than inline TVFs because they return table variables.

Example:

CREATE FUNCTION dbo.GetHighSalaryEmployees()
RETURNS @Result TABLE 
(
    Id INT, 
    Name NVARCHAR(100), 
    Salary DECIMAL(10,2)
)
AS
BEGIN
    INSERT INTO @Result
    SELECT Id, Name, Salary 
    FROM Employees 
    WHERE Salary > 60000;
    RETURN;
END;

💡 Use when multiple steps or logic are required before producing results.

When to Use User-Defined Functions

UDFs are ideal for reusable logic, but choosing the right type matters.

  • Use Scalar UDFs for formatting, calculations, validation.
  • Use Inline TVFs for fast, parameterized data retrieval.
  • Use Multi-Statement TVFs for complex row-processing logic.
  • Avoid UDFs in large SELECT queries if performance is critical.

💡 Inline TVFs offer the best performance and optimization.
